T1  - “CONVENTIONAL” MONETARY POLICY IN OLG MODELS: REVISITING THE ASSET-SUBSTITUTION CHANNEL
AU  - Hu, Guanliang
AU  - Ma, Guoxuan
AU  - Qiao, Wei
AU  - Wallace, Neil
Y1  - 2023/08/01
PY  - 2023
DA  - 2023/08/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12618
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 875
EP  - 892
VL  - 64
IS  - 3
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12618
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Abstract Conventional monetary policy involves actions by the monetary and fiscal authorities: the former sets a nominal interest rate and the latter sets lump-sum taxes to finance the implied flow of interest payments on government debt. We model such policy within an overlapping generations framework and show that absent any other frictions the magnitude of the nominal interest rate gives rise to asset substitution between government debt and either private debt or capital?substitution that has both real and nominal effects. Such substitution is not in standard New Keynesian models because their dynastic specification implies that government debt is not net wealth.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - BARGAINING OVER TAXES AND ENTITLEMENTS IN THE ERA OF UNEQUAL GROWTH
AU  - Azzimonti, Marina
AU  - Karpuska, Laura
AU  - Mihalache, Gabriel
Y1  - 2023/08/01
PY  - 2023
DA  - 2023/08/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12625
T2  - International Economic Review
JF  - International Economic Review
JO  - International Economic Review
JA  - International Economic Review
SP  - 893
EP  - 941
VL  - 64
IS  - 3
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0020-6598
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/iere.12625
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Abstract Entitlements have become an increasing component of total government spending in the United States over the last six decades. Using a political-economy model where parties bargain over taxes and entitlements, we argue that such dynamics can be explained by two factors: ?unequal growth,? where top earners became richer while the income of the bottom 50% stagnated, and budget rules that provide bargaining power to low-income earners through a ?status quo effect.? In a model calibrated to the United States, we show that sustained bargaining power by a party representing the poor results in a rising share of entitlements consistent with the data.
ER  - 

